	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB0099_01.jpg"/> The person in question has given us the following information: During the rule of the <term
					type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_czechs">Czechs</term> we did very well in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/700646/mukacheve.html">Várpalánka</placeName>. They never abused Jews and we enjoyed equal rights
				with the others. When the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1034" type="subject">Hungarians</term> came
				in, they took away the trade licenses and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-330" type="subject">abused the
					Jewish inhabitants</term> of the village quite a lot. There was a garrison in the village and the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">soldiers</term> marching there sang satirical songs,
				the target of which was Jews. Later, incited by young ethnic <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>
				they broke in some Jewish homes, led by officers called <persName ref="#ehri_et_kiss">Kiss</persName> and <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_boldog_istvan">István Boldog</persName>. They went to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/700646/mukacheve.html"
					>Munkács</placeName> every evening and they broke in Jewish houses under the pretext that those were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">military</term> exercises. They robbed the Jews of
				every possession and beat them to a pulp. They came back to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/700646/mukacheve.html"
					>Palánka</placeName> at 12 o'clock at night and continued with us. Terrible noises, screams could be heard in the night. We lived
				through terrible times, trembling in horrible fear; that was the time when I got a heart ailment. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1034" type="subject">army</term> terrorized the inhabitants all the time
				and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-345" type="subject">beat Jewish men horribly</term> without any
				reason. A lance corporal called <persName ref="#ehri_et_voros">Vörös</persName> also behaved in such a base way that we did not dare
				go out to the street in the evening at all. That was the beginning of the terror for us. Then we already had to be in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hiding</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Hungary</placeName>; we did not dare sleep at home, we spent the nights at our
				relatives living in nearby towns, where we <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">slept in
					barns and haylofts</term>. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1034" type="subject"
					>Hungarians</term> had already treated us in an inhuman and cruel way before the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">German</term> invasion. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1034" type="subject">Hungarians</term> committed more horrible tortures
				than the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">Germans</term> did in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">Germany</term>. They completely ruined us
				psychically. 70 Jewish families lived in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/700646/mukacheve.html">Várpalánka</placeName>, most
				of them were tradesmen and craftsmen. Most of them lived in good financial conditions and were not short of anything. I was a
				dressmaker and I earned as much as I needed. It was the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1034"
					type="subject">Hungarian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">police</term> of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/700646/mukacheve.html">Munkács</placeName> who ordered the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-335" type="subject">anti-Jewish decrees</term> against us. The inhabitants
				of the village behaved in a relatively considerate way, except the ethnic <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans"
					>German</term> members of the organization Jugendheiz, who were the followers of <persName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000185">Hitler</persName> and acted in a shameful manner towards us. We
				wanted to give 10,000 pengős to the notary's office in order to let us stay in the village but they could not do anything. After <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-754" type="subject">Passover</term> they took us to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> in the brickyard of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/700646/mukacheve.html">Munkács</placeName>. There the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1034" type="subject">Hungarian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">policemen</term> forced the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term> to crawl on their bellies in the mud and
				hit their heads with rifle butts. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1034" type="subject"
					>Hungarian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">policemen</term> and 3 <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>, one of them was called <persName ref="#ehri_et_sefcsenko"
					>Sefcsenko</persName>, beat the young boys extremely hard, some of them they beat to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">death</term>. We were already so desperate that we
				could hardly wait to be taken to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>. That
				is, they lied that they would take us to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>
				in the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/719894/hortobagy.html">Hortobágy</placeName>. They entrained us in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/700646/mukacheve.html">Munkács</placeName> but they did not give us water, nor did they give us a
				bucket for toilet purposes. In <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/715839/satoraljaujhely.html">Sátoraljaújhely</placeName>,
				Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-560" type="subject">labour servicemen</term> saw us and they
				wanted to give us water, which the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1034" type="subject">Hungarian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">policemen</term> did not allow them to do so. 80 of
				us were in a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">cattle car</term>: fainting old people,
				crying little <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>. They handed us over
				to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">Germans</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName>. The <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName> told us that they would take us to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> at a good place. <pb n="2"
					facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB0099_02.jpg"/> On our arrival in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2"
					>Auschwitz</placeName> they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">separated</term> me
				from the rest of my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">family</term> and I had no idea
				what was in store for me. We did not even want to believe it from a <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_slovaks"
					>Slovakian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term> there that they were burning our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">family</term> members in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">crematorium</term>. They took all the expectant <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">mothers</term> away and still we managed to hide an
				expectant <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term>, who gave birth to her <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child</term> in secret; of course we arranged it so
				that the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child</term> would not remain alive. When
				we arrived in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/6558164/geislingen.html">Geislingen</placeName>, we thought that it would be a
				very good place to stay, because we could sit at a table, where we had to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> 12 hours a day. We did well in the
				beginning, but later <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-485" type="subject">Capos</term> came and stole our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food.</term> We slept in cold rooms in the winter and
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> in a factory, which was not
				heated. Our hands got frostbitten and the flesh between our fingers cracked. After <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-754" type="subject">Passover</term>, they took us to Münchenallsch where
				we stayed only for two weeks, then they entrained us. We did not receive anything else to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">eat</term> than a little <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> for a week. We <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-570" type="subject">starved</term> very, very much, we lost weight, we
				were nothing but skin and bones and several <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject"
					>men</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died.</term> The <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_americans">American</term> troops <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573"
					type="subject">liberated</term> us on <date when="1945-05-01">1st May</date>. They supplied us with the best things imaginable,
				like first-class <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>, <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836">clothes</term> and shoes. They took us to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2896566/illdorf.html">Illdorf</placeName> near Stahldoch, where we stayed for four weeks, then we
				were taken to a home for members of the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-317">Hitlerjugend</orgName>
				in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2927464/feldafing.html">Feldafing</placeName>. We received excellent medical treatment. A
					<term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_czechs">Czech</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1034" type="subject">soldie</term>r came for us and told us not to speak
					<term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term> anywhere; they put us in a car and after a nine-hour
				journey we arrived in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3068160/pilsen.html">Pilsen</placeName>. In the <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_czechs">Czech</term> villages, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824"
					type="subject">children</term>, old people and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject"
					>men</term> ran to meet us and received us very happily. We were crying from emotion when we saw that welcome boards were put on
				view and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">mothers</term> were holding their <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term> up in the windows. Then they took us
				to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> by bus and from there, we came to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Pest</placeName> through <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3060972/bratislava.html">Pozsony</placeName>. Now I am going home to see whether my little <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">son</term> is there and then we will <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">go</term> together to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-906" type="subject">Palestine</term>. I cannot imagine living among the
				evil people at home, so I would like to work on building of our new homeland in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-906" type="subject">Palestine</term>.</p>
		</body>
